{"title_page": "Kokoni", "text_new": "\n\n<!-- Begin Infobox Dogbreed. The text of the article should go AFTER this section. See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Dog_breeds#Infobox_Dogbreed_template \nfor full explanation of the syntax used in this template. -->\n{{Infobox dog breed \n|name     = Kokoni\n|image    = File:KokoniPurebredDogsGreeceGreekCreamWhiteAdult.jpg\n|image_alt =\n|image_caption = A cream-colored Kokoni\n|altname  =\n|nickname = \n|country  = Greece\n<!-----Traits----->\n|maleweight   = \n|femaleweight = \n|maleheight   = \n|femaleheight = \n|coat         = \n|color        = \n|litter_size  = \n|life_span    = \n<!-----Classification and standards----->\n|fcigroup   = \n|fcisection =  \n|fcinum     = \n|fcistd     = \n|akcgroup   = \n|akcstd     = \n|akcfss     = \n|akcmisc    = \n|ankcgroup  = \n|ankcstd    = \n|ckcgroup   =  \n|ckcstd     = \n|ckcmisc    = \n|kcukgroup  = \n|kcukstd    = \n|nzkcgroup  = \n|nzkcstd    = \n|ukcgroup   = \n|ukcstd     = \n|rscegroup  = \n|rscesect   = \n|rscestd    = \n|notrecognized = \n|extinct    = \n<!-----Notes----->\n|note = Recognized by the [[Greek Kennel Club]]\n}}  \n<!-- End Infobox Dogbreed info. Article Begins Here -->\n\nThe '''Kokoni''' ({{lang-el|\u039a\u03bf\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9}}) is a small domestic [[dog breed]] from [[Greece]], only recently established as a [[Breed standard|standardized breed]].  The [[foundation stock]], a general [[landrace]] of small dogs of the region, are widely found throughout the country, have traditionally been more common in urban areas, and have been a popular companion of Greeks for centuries. This breed is also known as the Small Greek Domestic Dog.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name {{lang|el-Latn|Kokoni}} probably derives from the word {{lang|el|\u03ba\u03bf\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd\u03b1}} {{lang|el-Latn|kokona}} which is another word for 'daughter' in [[Modern Greek]]. In past times, the daughter's life was mostly in and around the house, so the Kokoni dog was the 'daughter's dog' or the 'dog for the house', unlike the [[hunting dog]]s or the [[livestock guardian dog]]s.\n\n== Breed History ==\nThe Kokoni dog, originated in Malta and has been a part of Greek life for hundreds of years along with their slightly larger cousins, the [[Alopekis|Alopeki]]'s, a breed once thought to be a different variety of the same breed. The knowledge of their heritage has been lost to history, but ancient wall decorations, vases, coins, and other pottery pieces exhibit images of these little dogs, generally depicted as the companions to women and children, particularly those in the aristocracy. Many of these little dogs have been employed as multipurpose dogs throughout history, particularly for those with more modest means, and they proved effective as hunting dogs, helping to find and capture small game, both mammals and birds, as well as ridding the house and barns of pests and even occasionally helping herd livestock, those that didn\u2019t find a domestic home even managed to survive both in and outside of the Grecian cities. The unrestricted breeding ended up developing into a particularly healthy breed compared to many breeds with no specific disorders that are more prevalent to their breed.  This breed is very popular in and around Greece, but it has little representation outside of its home country and is not yet recognized by the major kennel clubs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wagwalking.com/breed/kokoni|title=Kokoni {{!}} Dog Breed Facts and Information - Wag! Dog Walking|website=WagWalking|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> They gained recognition with the Greek Kennel Club, after a group of [[wiktionary:cynophile|cynophiles]] clarified the breed standards of Kokoni's and [[Alopekis|Alopeki]]'s.\n\n==Breed recognition==\n[[File:Kokoni dog at international dog show in Greece.jpg|thumb|left|A black and tan Small Greek Domestic Dog]]\nA [[Breed standard|standardized breed]] named the Kokoni has been developed from [[landrace]] dogs of Greece, and is formally recognized as a breed by the [http://www.koe.gr/index.php/en Greek Kennel Club].The details below pertain to this breed. They are not yet recognized by the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Cynologique Internationale]] (the major international [[breed registry]] for dogs). They are often confused with the long-haired Dachshund, or a Cocker Spaniel mixture. Their legs are longer than a dachshund, which lifts their belly and chest more off the ground.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.milouchouchou.com/les-races-rares/kokoni|title=Kokoni|last=Vandersteen|first=Francis|website=www.milouchouchou.com|language=fr-fr|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  \n\nThe blond dog known as \"Satchel\" in the 2005 film Bewitched with Nicole Kidman and Will Ferrell is a small Greek domestic dog.   \n\n== Appearance ==\nA small dog with a trunk longer than its height, hair short on the face and front of the limbs, moderately long on the trunk and neck, and longer on the tail and buttocks. Triangular head with fallen ears. The tail forms a semicircle. With fast and lively movement.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.koe.gr/index.php/el/greekbreeds/kokoni|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9|last=User|first=Super|website=www.koe.gr|language=el-gr|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  \n\nImportant notes about the Kokoni's general appearance include: Body length longer than its height. Nose length less than the length of the skull. Skull circumference slightly smaller than its length.  \n\n====== Height and Weight ======\n[[File:Cadela da ra\u00e7a Kokoni.jpg|thumb|The coat is may be slightly wavy]]This breed of dog is considered to be of a small to medium size. Their height is 24 to 28 centimeters (9.45 to 11.02 inches) for males, and 23 to 27 centimeters (9.05 to 10.63 inches) for females. Their weight ranges from 4 to 8 kilograms (8.81 to 17.63 lb). There is a tolerable deviation of 1 cm for height, and 1 kg for weight, above or below the limits. The tolerable deviation range for height is 23 to 29 cm (9.05 to 11.42 inches) for males, and 22 to 28 cm (8.66 to 11.02 inches) for females. The tolerable deviation range for weight is 3 to 9 kg (6.61 to 19.85 lb). A dog outside the tolerable deviation range for height cannot be considered a full purebred Kokoni, however, a full purebred Kokoni can be over the tolerable deviation range for weight, as this breed is prone to overeating, and weight gain, especially if they are spayed or neutered.   \n\n====== Colors ======\nThis breed comes in a variety of colors and combinations of colors, such as black and tan, blonde, cream, and white. All colors and patterns are acceptable in the breed standard, although some are rarer than others. Some colors, such as black, are dominant, while others, like brown/liver, are recessive. Dilute Kokoni's, such as blue or lilac, are extremely rare. Since dilution and liver are both recessive and relatively rare, Isabella/Lilac is the rarest color of Kokoni.  \n\n====== Coat ======\nThe coat of the Kokoni is of three lengths, and is easy to groom. It can be straight or wavy, but it should always feel silky. The coat is rich, dense and weatherproof. Straight coated Kokoni's are genetically dominant to wavy coated Kokoni's; as such, wavy coated Kokoni's are rarer than straight coated Kokoni's. The coat of the Kokoni will be fully expressed by the time the Kokoni reaches two years of age. \n\n====== Tail ======\n[[File:Dog tails types.svg|thumb|Kokoni's can have tails like images 4 & 5; at rest they may appear like image 7, without it being a mistake.]]\nThe sickle-shaped tail of the Kokoni is usually long. The dog holds its tail up high, and has an elegant curve. The coat of this dog forms a brush under its tail, often described as a fan or feather tail. It is carried high, forming a semicircle, its tip resting on the back. It is covered with rich hair, forming a tuft. During the stop or rest, it may fall, without it being a mistake. In the tail and back part of the buttocks the dogs coat is even longer with a length of 8-14 cm (3.15 to 5.5 in). The beautiful tail, that the Kokoni fabulously flaunts, can start showing up at around 6 months of age, but will not be full-length until 9 months to 15 months of age.\n\n====== Eyes ======\nThis breed of dog has large eyes which vary in shape from round to more of an almond shape. They are bright and are not deep-set. The color goes with the color of the coat, but they will never be transparent or blue. Known eye color possibilities include, Brown, Dark Brown, Amber, Light Amber, and Hazel.  \n\n====== Ears ======\nTriangular, medium size, drooping and agile. Located relatively high, above the imaginary line of the eye, they are covered by short hair. Some dogs have longer hairs on the outside, from the base to the middle of the ear. Part of the ears or the whole ear, covered by short and smooth hair 1 cm (0.40 in) long or longer. <ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n====== Muzzle ======\nThe muzzle \"tapers easily to the nose\", and the top-line is level. The nose of the has well-opened nostrils. It is not large compared to the muzzle, and it is moist, flat, and level on the front surface. The jaws are strong, with scissor-bite teeth.\n\n==Health==\nThis is a deep-chested, sturdy, and agile breed, capable of great speeds and valued for its stamina.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}  The breed generally has good longevity and lives into their late teens.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}  Major health issues are not known.\n\n===Temperament===\n\nKokoni's are like all other dogs in that they can display a wide range of temperaments, behaviors, dispositions, and traits. It is important to remember that temperament and personality are unique to each dog, and the following statements are generalities. \n\nKokoni's have a loud, strong bark for their size though they do not bark much. The Kokoni is said to have an even temper and gentle disposition, and to be lively, cheerful, amiable and not generally aggressive or timid. Other behavioral claims are that they enjoy company, though may initially be standoffish with strangers.{{clarify|date=February 2020|reason=Um, how is this supposed to be in any way different from EVERY DOG BREED ON EARTH?}}  Breeders claim they are intelligent, easily trained, and very devoted to and protective of their keepers.{{citation needed|date=February 2020|reason=Behavioral claims like this almost always need to be deleted as promotional nonsense.}}\n\n=== Grooming ===\nComb and brush regularly with a firm bristle brush, and bathe at least once a month, or when necessary. Small Greek Domestic Dogs shed moderately. It's a natural process of the hair growth cycle. Regular brushing reduces the amount of hair that sheds. Seasonal flea treatment is needed, but cutting the dog's hair by a professional groomer isn't necessary. Clean tear ducts with a warm wet wash cloth daily or once a week at minimum. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.koe.gr/index.php/el/greekbreeds/kokoni The Kennel Club of Greece's breed standard]\n\n[[Category:Dog breeds originating in Greece]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n<!-- Begin Infobox Dogbreed. The text of the article should go AFTER this section. See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Dog_breeds#Infobox_Dogbreed_template \nfor full explanation of the syntax used in this template. -->\n{{Infobox dog breed \n|name     = Kokoni\n|image    = File:KokoniPurebredDogsGreeceGreekCreamWhiteAdult.jpg\n|image_alt =\n|image_caption = A cream-colored Kokoni\n|altname  =\n|nickname = \n|country  = Greece\n<!-----Traits----->\n|maleweight   = \n|femaleweight = \n|maleheight   = \n|femaleheight = \n|coat         = \n|color        = \n|litter_size  = \n|life_span    = \n<!-----Classification and standards----->\n|fcigroup   = \n|fcisection =  \n|fcinum     = \n|fcistd     = \n|akcgroup   = \n|akcstd     = \n|akcfss     = \n|akcmisc    = \n|ankcgroup  = \n|ankcstd    = \n|ckcgroup   =  \n|ckcstd     = \n|ckcmisc    = \n|kcukgroup  = \n|kcukstd    = \n|nzkcgroup  = \n|nzkcstd    = \n|ukcgroup   = \n|ukcstd     = \n|rscegroup  = \n|rscesect   = \n|rscestd    = \n|notrecognized = \n|extinct    = \n<!-----Notes----->\n|note = Recognized by the [[Greek Kennel Club]]\n}}  \n<!-- End Infobox Dogbreed info. Article Begins Here -->\n\nThe '''Kokoni''' ({{lang-el|\u039a\u03bf\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9}}) is a small domestic [[dog breed]] from [[Greece]], only recently established as a [[Breed standard|standardized breed]].  The [[foundation stock]], a general [[landrace]] of small dogs of the region, are widely found throughout the country, have traditionally been more common in urban areas, and have been a popular companion of Greeks for centuries. This breed is also known as the Small Greek Domestic Dog.\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name {{lang|el-Latn|Kokoni}} probably derives from the word {{lang|el|\u03ba\u03bf\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd\u03b1}} {{lang|el-Latn|kokona}} which is another word for 'daughter' in [[Modern Greek]]. In past times, the daughter's life was mostly in and around the house, so the Kokoni dog was the 'daughter's dog' or the 'dog for the house', unlike the [[hunting dog]]s or the [[livestock guardian dog]]s.\n\n== Breed History ==\nThe Kokoni dog, originated in Malta and has been a part of Greek life for hundreds of years along with their slightly larger cousins, the [[Alopekis|Alopeki]]'s, a breed once thought to be a different variety of the same breed. The knowledge of their heritage has been lost to history, but ancient wall decorations, vases, coins, and other pottery pieces exhibit images of these little dogs, generally depicted as the companions to women and children, particularly those in the aristocracy. Many of these little dogs have been employed as multipurpose dogs throughout history, particularly for those with more modest means, and they proved effective as hunting dogs, helping to find and capture small game, both mammals and birds, as well as ridding the house and barns of pests and even occasionally helping herd livestock, those that didn\u2019t find a domestic home even managed to survive both in and outside of the Grecian cities. The unrestricted breeding ended up developing into a particularly healthy breed compared to many breeds with no specific disorders that are more prevalent to their breed.  This breed is very popular in and around Greece, but it has little representation outside of its home country and is not yet recognized by the major kennel clubs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wagwalking.com/breed/kokoni|title=Kokoni {{!}} Dog Breed Facts and Information - Wag! Dog Walking|website=WagWalking|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> They gained recognition with the Greek Kennel Club, after a group of [[wiktionary:cynophile|cynophiles]] clarified the breed standards of Kokoni's and [[Alopekis|Alopeki]]'s.\n\n==Breed recognition==\n[[File:Kokoni dog at international dog show in Greece.jpg|thumb|left|A black and tan Small Greek Domestic Dog]]\nA [[Breed standard|standardized breed]] named the Kokoni has been developed from [[landrace]] dogs of Greece, and is formally recognized as a breed by the [http://www.koe.gr/index.php/en Greek Kennel Club].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koe.gr/index.php/en|title=Kennel Club of Greece|website=www.koe.gr|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> The details below pertain to this breed. They are not yet recognized by the [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Cynologique Internationale]] (the major international [[breed registry]] for dogs). They are often confused with the long-haired Dachshund, or a Cocker Spaniel mixture. Their legs are longer than a dachshund, which lifts their belly and chest more off the ground.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.milouchouchou.com/les-races-rares/kokoni|title=Kokoni|last=Vandersteen|first=Francis|website=www.milouchouchou.com|language=fr-fr|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  \n\nThe blond dog known as \"Satchel\" in the 2005 film Bewitched with Nicole Kidman and Will Ferrell is a small Greek domestic dog.   \n\n== Appearance ==\nA small dog with a trunk longer than its height, hair short on the face and front of the limbs, moderately long on the trunk and neck, and longer on the tail and buttocks. Triangular head with fallen ears. The tail forms a semicircle. With fast and lively movement.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.koe.gr/index.php/el/greekbreeds/kokoni|title=\u039a\u03bf\u03ba\u03cc\u03bd\u03b9|last=User|first=Super|website=www.koe.gr|language=el-gr|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  \n\nImportant notes about the Kokoni's general appearance include: Body length longer than its height. Nose length less than the length of the skull. Skull circumference slightly smaller than its length.  \n\n====== Height and Weight ======\n[[File:Cadela da ra\u00e7a Kokoni.jpg|thumb|The coat is may be slightly wavy]]This breed of dog is considered to be of a small to medium size. Their height is 24 to 28 centimeters (9.45 to 11.02 inches) for males, and 23 to 27 centimeters (9.05 to 10.63 inches) for females. Their weight ranges from 4 to 8 kilograms (8.81 to 17.63 lb). There is a tolerable deviation of 1 cm for height, and 1 kg for weight, above or below the limits. The tolerable deviation range for height is 23 to 29 cm (9.05 to 11.42 inches) for males, and 22 to 28 cm (8.66 to 11.02 inches) for females. The tolerable deviation range for weight is 3 to 9 kg (6.61 to 19.85 lb). A dog outside the tolerable deviation range for height cannot be considered a full purebred Kokoni, however, a full purebred Kokoni can be over the tolerable deviation range for weight, as this breed is prone to overeating, and weight gain, especially if they are spayed or neutered.   \n\n====== Colors ======\nThis breed comes in a variety of colors and combinations of colors, such as black and tan, blonde, cream, and white. All colors and patterns are acceptable in the breed standard, although some are rarer than others. Some colors, such as black, are dominant, while others, like brown/liver, are recessive. Dilute Kokoni's, such as blue or lilac, are extremely rare. Since dilution and liver are both recessive and relatively rare, Isabella/Lilac is the rarest color of Kokoni.  \n\n====== Coat ======\nThe coat of the Kokoni is of three lengths, and is easy to groom. It can be straight or wavy, but it should always feel silky. The coat is rich, dense and weatherproof. Straight coated Kokoni's are genetically dominant to wavy coated Kokoni's; as such, wavy coated Kokoni's are rarer than straight coated Kokoni's. The coat of the Kokoni will be fully expressed by the time the Kokoni reaches two years of age. \n\n====== Tail ======\n[[File:Dog tails types.svg|thumb|Kokoni's can have tails like images 4 & 5; at rest they may appear like image 7, without it being a mistake.]]\nThe sickle-shaped tail of the Kokoni is usually long. The dog holds its tail up high, and has an elegant curve. The coat of this dog forms a brush under its tail, often described as a fan or feather tail. It is carried high, forming a semicircle, its tip resting on the back. It is covered with rich hair, forming a tuft. During the stop or rest, it may fall, without it being a mistake. In the tail and back part of the buttocks the dogs coat is even longer with a length of 8-14 cm (3.15 to 5.5 in). The beautiful tail, that the Kokoni fabulously flaunts, can start showing up at around 6 months of age, but will not be full-length until 9 months to 15 months of age.\n\n====== Eyes ======\nThis breed of dog has large eyes which vary in shape from round to more of an almond shape. They are bright and are not deep-set. The color goes with the color of the coat, but they will never be transparent or blue. Known eye color possibilities include, Brown, Dark Brown, Amber, Light Amber, and Hazel.  \n\n====== Ears ======\nTriangular, medium size, drooping and agile. Located relatively high, above the imaginary line of the eye, they are covered by short hair. Some dogs have longer hairs on the outside, from the base to the middle of the ear. Part of the ears or the whole ear, covered by short and smooth hair 1 cm (0.40 in) long or longer. <ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n====== Muzzle ======\nThe muzzle \"tapers easily to the nose\", and the top-line is level. The nose of the has well-opened nostrils. It is not large compared to the muzzle, and it is moist, flat, and level on the front surface. The jaws are strong, with scissor-bite teeth.\n\n==Health==\nThis is a deep-chested, sturdy, and agile breed, capable of great speeds and valued for its stamina.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}  The breed generally has good longevity and lives into their late teens.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}  Major health issues are not known.\n\n===Temperament===\n\nKokoni's are like all other dogs in that they can display a wide range of temperaments, behaviors, dispositions, and traits. It is important to remember that temperament and personality are unique to each dog, and the following statements are generalities. \n\nKokoni's have a loud, strong bark for their size though they do not bark much. The Kokoni is said to have an even temper and gentle disposition, and to be lively, cheerful, amiable and not generally aggressive or timid. Other behavioral claims are that they enjoy company, though may initially be standoffish with strangers.{{clarify|date=February 2020|reason=Um, how is this supposed to be in any way different from EVERY DOG BREED ON EARTH?}}  Breeders claim they are intelligent, easily trained, and very devoted to and protective of their keepers.{{citation needed|date=February 2020|reason=Behavioral claims like this almost always need to be deleted as promotional nonsense.}}\n\n=== Grooming ===\nComb and brush regularly with a firm bristle brush, and bathe at least once a month, or when necessary. Small Greek Domestic Dogs shed moderately. It's a natural process of the hair growth cycle. Regular brushing reduces the amount of hair that sheds. Seasonal flea treatment is needed, but cutting the dog's hair by a professional groomer isn't necessary. Clean tear ducts with a warm wet wash cloth daily or once a week at minimum. \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.koe.gr/index.php/el/greekbreeds/kokoni The Kennel Club of Greece's breed standard]\n\n[[Category:Dog breeds originating in Greece]]\n", "name_user": "Adelexylem", "label": "safe", "comment": "Superfluous citation after external link.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kokoni"}
{"title_page": "Joey King", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Joey King on KidsPickFlicks.jpg\n| caption            = King in February 2013\n| name               = Joey King\n| birth_name         = Joey Lynn King\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1999|7|30}}\n| birth_place        = {{nowrap|[[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]], U.S.}}\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| family             = [[Hunter King]] (sister)\n| signature          = Joey king signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Joey Lynn King'''<ref name=\"TVGuide-bio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/joey-king/304284/ |title=Joey King |work=TV Guide |accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> (born July 30, 1999)<ref name=\"tvsa\">{{cite web |title=Joey King {{!}} TVSA |url=https://www.tvsa.co.za/actors/viewactor.aspx?actorid=14843 |website=www.tvsa.co.za |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> is an American actress. She first gained recognition for portraying [[Ramona Quimby]] in the comedy film ''[[Ramona and Beezus]]'' (2010), an adaptation of [[Beverly Cleary]]'s book series ''[[Beezus and Ramona]]''. King has also appeared in the films ''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]'' (2011), ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'' (2012), ''[[Oz the Great and Powerful]]'' (2013), ''[[The Conjuring]]'' (2013), ''[[White House Down]]'' (2013), ''[[Independence Day: Resurgence]]'' (2016), ''[[Wish Upon]]'' (2017), ''[[The Kissing Booth]]'' (2018), and ''[[Slender Man (film)|Slender Man]]'' (2018). King received critical acclaim for her starring role in the true crime drama series ''[[The Act (TV series)|The Act]]'' (2019) and earned both [[Primetime Emmy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations for her performance.\n\n== Early life ==\nKing was born in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Hollywood.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/joey-king-57654943/ |title=Joey King |work=Hollywood.com |accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> She has two older sisters, actresses Kelli and [[Hunter King]]. King has stated that she is \"part Jewish and part Christian, but [...] mostly [[Jewish]].\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Interview: Joey King |url=http://tommy2.net/content/?p=31448 |title=Tommy2.net |publisher=Tommy2.net |accessdate=June 19, 2013}}</ref>{{better source|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Career ==\nKing made her film debut in ''[[Reign Over Me]]'' as [[Adam Sandler]]'s character's daughter. She  then voiced the yellow fur ball Katie in the animated feature ''[[Horton Hears a Who! (film)|Horton Hears a Who!]]'' (2008), and Beaver in ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]'' (2009). She also appeared in ''[[Quarantine (2008 film)|Quarantine]]'' (2008). In 2010, she guest-starred in the series ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]''. She was also featured in ''[[The Suite Life of Zack & Cody]]'' as Emily Mason in two episodes. Other television appearances include ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]'', ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'', and ''[[Medium (TV series)|Medium]]''.\n\nKing's first lead role was in the 2010 film ''[[Ramona and Beezus]]'', an adaptation of the [[Beverly Cleary]] book series, starring as [[Ramona Quimby]] opposite [[Selena Gomez]] as her older sister, [[Beezus Quimby]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Cindy|title='Ramona' star is ready for wackiness|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2009-02-05-beezus-and-ramona_N.htm|newspaper=USA Today|date=February 2, 2009|accessdate=June 12, 2010}}</ref> She also released a single for the movie called \"Ramona Blue\".\n\nKing was featured in ''[[Battle: Los Angeles]]'', where she played a girl named Kirsten. Also in 2011, she co-starred in ''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]'' as the younger daughter of [[Steve Carell]] and [[Julianne Moore]]. As well, she appeared in [[Taylor Swift]]'s \"[[Mean (song)|Mean]]\" music video as a young student at the school cafeteria rejected by her peers.\n\nKing had a role in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s third [[Batman]] film, ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'' (2012), as a young [[Talia al Ghul]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Wales|first=George |url=http://www.totalfilm.com/news/joey-king-reveals-huge-dark-knight-rises-spoiler |title=Joey King reveals HUGE Dark Knight Rises spoiler |website=TotalFilm.com|date=January 20, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> She also filmed the short-lived comedy series ''Bent'', had guest appearances in ''[[New Girl (TV series)|New Girl]]'' and was on the final episode of ''[[The Haunting Hour: The Series]]'', \"Goodwill Towards Men.\" In 2013, King appeared in ''[[Oz the Great and Powerful]]'' with [[James Franco]] and [[Zach Braff]], ''[[White House Down]]'' with [[Channing Tatum]] and [[Jamie Foxx]], ''[[Family Weekend]]'', and ''[[The Conjuring]]'' with [[Mackenzie Foy]] and [[Vera Farmiga]]. In 2014, she appeared in ''[[Wish I Was Here]]'' with ''Oz'' co-star Zach Braff, as well as in ''[[Fargo (TV series)|Fargo]]'' as Greta Grimly, daughter of police officer Gus Grimly ([[Colin Hanks]]).\n\nIn 2016, King was cast as the daughter of the character of [[Courtney Love]] in the coming-of-age drama film ''The Possibility of Fireflies''.<ref name=\"V-F\">{{cite web |last=McNary|first=Dave |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/festivals/courtney-love-joey-king-possibility-of-fireflies-movie-1201773041/ |title=Courtney Love, Joey King Starring in 'Possibility of Fireflies' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=May 12, 2016 |accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref> She played the lead character Clare in the 2017 horror-thriller film ''[[Wish Upon]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Anita|last=Busch |url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/joey-king-next-horror-film-wish-upon-annabelle-director-john-leonetti-broad-green-1201804174/ |title=Joey King Will Lead 'Annabelle' Helmer's Next Project 'Wish Upon' |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 16, 2016 |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she starred in ''[[The Kissing Booth]]'' alongside [[Jacob Elordi]] and [[Joel Courtney]].\n\nIn 2019, she starred alongside [[Patricia Arquette]] in the true crime anthology television series ''[[The Act (TV series)|The Act]]'' on [[Hulu]]. King plays [[Gypsy Rose Blanchard]] and Arquette plays her mother Dee Dee.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowenbank |first1=Starr |title=See Patricia Arquette and Joey King in the First Trailer for The Act |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/movies-tv/a26309720/the-act-trailer-patricia-arquette-joey-king/ |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |work=Elle |date=February 12, 2019}}</ref> She also appeared on the 4th season of CBS comedy ''[[Life in Pieces]]'' as Morgan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hall |first1=Gerrad |title=Sisters Hunter and Joey King hope 'Life in Pieces' is just the beginning of more work together: 'Put us in your s\u2011\u2011\u2011!' |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/18/sisters-hunter-joey-king-life-in-pieces/ |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nKing is represented by talent agent [[Dan Spilo]], who also competed on ''[[Survivor: Island of the Idols]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/11/14/survivor-contestant-accused-of-unwanted-touching-and-his-accuser-was-voted-off/|title=\u2018Survivor\u2019 contestant accused of unwanted touching \u2014 and his accuser was voted off|last=Sarner|first=Lauren|date=2019-11-14|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Reign Over Me]]''\n| Gina Fineman\n| Uncredited{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2008\n| ''[[Horton Hears a Who! (film)|Horton Hears a Who!]]''\n| Katie\n| Voice role\n|-\n| ''[[Quarantine (2008 film)|Quarantine]]''\n| Briana\n|\n|- \n| 2009\n| ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]''\n| Beaver girl\n| Voice role\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Ramona and Beezus]]''\n| [[Ramona Quimby]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2011\n| ''[[Battle: Los Angeles]]''\n| Kirsten\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]''\n| Molly Weaver\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| data-sort-value=\"Dark Knight Rises, The\" | ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]''\n| Young [[Talia al Ghul]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2013\n| data-sort-value=\"Conjuring, The\" | ''[[The Conjuring]]''\n| Christine Perron\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Family Weekend]]''\n| Lucinda Smith-Dungy\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Oz the Great and Powerful]]''\n| China Girl/Girl in Wheelchair\n|\n|-\n| ''[[White House Down]]''\n| Emily Cale\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2014\n| data-sort-value=\"Boxcar Children, The\" | ''[[The Boxcar Children (film)|The Boxcar Children]]''\n| Jessie\n| Voice role\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Sound and the Fury, The\" | ''[[The Sound and the Fury (2014 film)|The Sound and the Fury]]''\n| Miss Quentin\n|\n|-\n|''[[Wish I Was Here]]''\n| Grace Bloom\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2015\n| ''[[Borealis (2015 film)|Borealis]]''\n| Aurora \n|\n|-\n| ''[[Stonewall (2015 film)|Stonewall]]''\n| Phoebe Winters\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Independence Day: Resurgence]]''\n| Samantha \"Sam\" Blackwell\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" | 2017\n| ''[[Going in Style (2017 film)|Going in Style]]''\n| Brooklyn\n|\n|-\n|''[[Smartass]]''\n| Freddie\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Wish Upon]]''\n| Clare Shannon\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2018\n| data-sort-value=\"Kissing Booth 1, The\" | ''[[The Kissing Booth]]''\n| Elle Evans\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Lie, The\" | ''[[The Lie (2018 film)|The Lie]]''\n| Kayla\n| \n|-\n| ''Radium Girls''\n| Bessie\n| \n|-\n|''[[Slender Man (film)|Slender Man]]''\n| Wren\n|\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Summer Oh Three\" | ''[[Summer '03]]''\n| Jamie\n|\n|-\n\n| 2019 \n| ''[[Zeroville (film)|Zeroville]]''\n| Zazi\n| \n|-\n| 2020\n| data-sort-value=\"Kissing Booth 2, The\" | ''[[The Kissing Booth 2]]'' \n| Elle Evans\n| Post-production<ref>{{cite web |url=https://deadline.com/2019/02/the-kissing-booth-2-sequel-set-netflix-joey-king-joel-courtney-1202557587/ |title='The Kissing 