ate=March 31, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6FaZ1wnUQ?url=http://www.youngartistawards.org/noms34.html |archivedate=April 2, 2013 |df= }}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2019\n| |[[2019 Kids' Choice Awards|Kids' Choice Awards]]\n| Favorite Movie Actress\n| data-sort-value=\"Kissing Booth, The\" | ''[[The Kissing Booth]]''\n| {{won}}\n|\n|-\n| |[[71st Primetime Emmy Awards|Primetime Emmy Awards]]\n| [[Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Limited Series or Movie|Outstanding Lead Actress in a Limited Series or Movie]]\n| data-sort-value=\"Act, The\" | ''[[The Act (TV series)|The Act]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2020\n| [[10th Critics' Choice Television Awards|Critics' Choice Television Awards]]\n| [[Critics' Choice Television Award for Best Actress in a Movie/Miniseries|Best Actress in a Limited Series or Television Movie]]\n|''The Act''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| [[77th Golden Globe Awards|Golden Globe Awards]]\n| [[Golden Globe Award for Best Actress \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film|Best Actress \u2013 Limited Series or Television Film]]\n|''The Act''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| [[24th Satellite Awards|Satellite Awards]]\n| [[Satellite Award for Best Actress \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film|Best Actress \u2013 Miniseries or Television Film]]\n|''The Act''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|-\n| [[26th Screen Actors Guild Awards|Screen Actors Guild Awards]]\n| [[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Miniseries or Television Movie|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Miniseries or Television Movie]]\n|''The Act''\n| {{nom}}\n|\n|}\n\nAt the 2015 [[Vancouver International Film Festival]], the Canadian Images features jury made an honourable mention recognizing King as an Emerging Actress for her performance in ''Borealis''.<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://archive.viff.org/e-blasts/viff/2015/20_BCSpotlightCanadianImagesAwards_VIFF2015_PR.html |date=October 3, 2015 |accessdate=October 11, 2015 |title=VIFF Announces BC Spotlight and Canadian Images Awards  |publisher=Vancouver International Film Festival}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name}}\n* {{Twitter}}\n* {{Instagram}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:King, Joey}}\n[[Category:1999 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American child actresses]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American voice actresses]]\n[[Category:Jewish American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Joey King on KidsPickFlicks.jpg\n| caption            = King in February 2013\n| name               = Joey King\n| birth_name         = Joey Lynn King\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1999|7|30}}\n| birth_place        = {{nowrap|[[Los Angeles|Los Angeles, California]], U.S.}}\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2006\u2013present\n| family             = [[Hunter King]] (sister)\n| signature          = Joey king signature.png\n}}\n\n'''Joey Lynn King'''<ref name=\"TVGuide-bio\">{{cite web |url=https://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/joey-king/304284/ |title=Joey King |work=TV Guide |accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> (born July 30, 1999)<ref name=\"tvsa\">{{cite web |title=Joey King {{!}} TVSA |url=https://www.tvsa.co.za/actors/viewactor.aspx?actorid=14843 |website=www.tvsa.co.za |accessdate=January 1, 2019}}</ref> is an American actress. She first gained recognition for portraying [[Ramona Quimby]] in the comedy film ''[[Ramona and Beezus]]'' (2010), an adaptation of [[Beverly Cleary]]'s book series ''[[Beezus and Ramona]]''. King has also appeared in the films ''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]'' (2011), ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'' (2012), ''[[Oz the Great and Powerful]]'' (2013), ''[[The Conjuring]]'' (2013), ''[[White House Down]]'' (2013), ''[[Independence Day: Resurgence]]'' (2016), ''[[Wish Upon]]'' (2017), ''[[The Kissing Booth]]'' (2018), and ''[[Slender Man (film)|Slender Man]]'' (2018). King received critical acclaim for her starring role in the true crime drama series ''[[The Act (TV series)|The Act]]'' (2019) and earned both [[Primetime Emmy Award]] and [[Golden Globe Award]] nominations for her performance.\n\n== Early life ==\nKing was born in Los Angeles.<ref name=\"Hollywood.com\">{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrities/joey-king-57654943/ |title=Joey King |work=Hollywood.com |accessdate=November 3, 2016}}</ref> She has two older sisters, actresses Kelli and [[Hunter King]]. King has stated that she is \"part Jewish and part Christian, but [...] mostly [[Jewish]].\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Interview: Joey King |url=http://tommy2.net/content/?p=31448 |title=Tommy2.net |publisher=Tommy2.net |accessdate=June 19, 2013}}</ref>{{better source|date=January 2020}}\n\n== Career ==\nKing made her film debut in ''[[Reign Over Me]]'' as [[Adam Sandler]]'s character's daughter. She  then voiced the yellow fur ball Katie in the animated feature ''[[Horton Hears a Who! (film)|Horton Hears a Who!]]'' (2008), and Beaver in ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]'' (2009). She also appeared in ''[[Quarantine (2008 film)|Quarantine]]'' (2008). In 2010, she guest-starred in the series ''[[Ghost Whisperer]]''. She was also featured in ''[[The Suite Life of Zack & Cody]]'' as Emily Mason in two episodes. Other television appearances include ''[[Entourage (U.S. TV series)|Entourage]]'', ''[[CSI: Crime Scene Investigation]]'', and ''[[Medium (TV series)|Medium]]''.\n\nKing's first lead role was in the 2010 film ''[[Ramona and Beezus]]'', an adaptation of the [[Beverly Cleary]] book series, starring as [[Ramona Quimby]] opposite [[Selena Gomez]] as her older sister, [[Beezus Quimby]].<ref>{{cite news|last=Clark|first=Cindy|title='Ramona' star is ready for wackiness|url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/movies/news/2009-02-05-beezus-and-ramona_N.htm|newspaper=USA Today|date=February 2, 2009|accessdate=June 12, 2010}}</ref> She also released a single for the movie called \"Ramona Blue\".\n\nKing was featured in ''[[Battle: Los Angeles]]'', where she played a girl named Kirsten. Also in 2011, she co-starred in ''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]'' as the younger daughter of [[Steve Carell]] and [[Julianne Moore]]. As well, she appeared in [[Taylor Swift]]'s \"[[Mean (song)|Mean]]\" music video as a young student at the school cafeteria rejected by her peers.\n\nKing had a role in [[Christopher Nolan]]'s third [[Batman]] film, ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]'' (2012), as a young [[Talia al Ghul]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Wales|first=George |url=http://www.totalfilm.com/news/joey-king-reveals-huge-dark-knight-rises-spoiler |title=Joey King reveals HUGE Dark Knight Rises spoiler |website=TotalFilm.com|date=January 20, 2012 |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref> She also filmed the short-lived comedy series ''Bent'', had guest appearances in ''[[New Girl (TV series)|New Girl]]'' and was on the final episode of ''[[The Haunting Hour: The Series]]'', \"Goodwill Towards Men.\" In 2013, King appeared in ''[[Oz the Great and Powerful]]'' with [[James Franco]] and [[Zach Braff]], ''[[White House Down]]'' with [[Channing Tatum]] and [[Jamie Foxx]], ''[[Family Weekend]]'', and ''[[The Conjuring]]'' with [[Mackenzie Foy]] and [[Vera Farmiga]]. In 2014, she appeared in ''[[Wish I Was Here]]'' with ''Oz'' co-star Zach Braff, as well as in ''[[Fargo (TV series)|Fargo]]'' as Greta Grimly, daughter of police officer Gus Grimly ([[Colin Hanks]]).\n\nIn 2016, King was cast as the daughter of the character of [[Courtney Love]] in the coming-of-age drama film ''The Possibility of Fireflies''.<ref name=\"V-F\">{{cite web |last=McNary|first=Dave |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/festivals/courtney-love-joey-king-possibility-of-fireflies-movie-1201773041/ |title=Courtney Love, Joey King Starring in 'Possibility of Fireflies' |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=May 12, 2016 |accessdate=June 30, 2016}}</ref> She played the lead character Clare in the 2017 horror-thriller film ''[[Wish Upon]]''.<ref>{{cite news |first=Anita|last=Busch |url=https://deadline.com/2016/08/joey-king-next-horror-film-wish-upon-annabelle-director-john-leonetti-broad-green-1201804174/ |title=Joey King Will Lead 'Annabelle' Helmer's Next Project 'Wish Upon' |work=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=August 16, 2016 |accessdate=August 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, she starred in ''[[The Kissing Booth]]'' alongside [[Jacob Elordi]] and [[Joel Courtney]].\n\nIn 2019, she starred alongside [[Patricia Arquette]] in the true crime anthology television series ''[[The Act (TV series)|The Act]]'' on [[Hulu]]. King plays [[Gypsy Rose Blanchard]] and Arquette plays her mother Dee Dee.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowenbank |first1=Starr |title=See Patricia Arquette and Joey King in the First Trailer for The Act |url=https://www.elle.com/culture/movies-tv/a26309720/the-act-trailer-patricia-arquette-joey-king/ |accessdate=February 20, 2019 |work=Elle |date=February 12, 2019}}</ref> She also appeared on the 4th season of CBS comedy ''[[Life in Pieces]]'' as Morgan.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hall |first1=Gerrad |title=Sisters Hunter and Joey King hope 'Life in Pieces' is just the beginning of more work together: 'Put us in your s\u2011\u2011\u2011!' |url=https://ew.com/tv/2019/04/18/sisters-hunter-joey-king-life-in-pieces/ |accessdate=April 30, 2019 |work=Entertainment Weekly |date=April 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\nKing is represented by talent agent [[Dan Spilo]], who also competed on ''[[Survivor: Island of the Idols]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/11/14/survivor-contestant-accused-of-unwanted-touching-and-his-accuser-was-voted-off/|title=\u2018Survivor\u2019 contestant accused of unwanted touching \u2014 and his accuser was voted off|last=Sarner|first=Lauren|date=2019-11-14|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=2019-11-14}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[Reign Over Me]]''\n| Gina Fineman\n| Uncredited{{citation needed|date=May 2016}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2008\n| ''[[Horton Hears a Who! (film)|Horton Hears a Who!]]''\n| Katie\n| Voice role\n|-\n| ''[[Quarantine (2008 film)|Quarantine]]''\n| Briana\n|\n|- \n| 2009\n| ''[[Ice Age: Dawn of the Dinosaurs]]''\n| Beaver girl\n| Voice role\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Ramona and Beezus]]''\n| [[Ramona Quimby]]\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2011\n| ''[[Battle: Los Angeles]]''\n| Kirsten\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Crazy, Stupid, Love]]''\n| Molly Weaver\n|\n|-\n| 2012\n| data-sort-value=\"Dark Knight Rises, The\" | ''[[The Dark Knight Rises]]''\n| Young [[Talia al Ghul]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2013\n| data-sort-value=\"Conjuring, The\" | ''[[The Conjuring]]''\n| Christine Perron\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Family Weekend]]''\n| Lucinda Smith-Dungy\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Oz the Great and Powerful]]''\n| China Girl/Girl in Wheelchair\n|\n|-\n| ''[[White House Down]]''\n| Emily Cale\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2014\n| data-sort-value=\"Boxcar Children, The\" | ''[[The Boxcar Children (film)|The Boxcar Children]]''\n| Jessie\n| Voice role\n|-\n| data-sort-value=\"Sound and the Fury, The\" | ''[[The Sound and the Fury (2014 film)|The Sound and the Fury]]''\n| Miss Quentin\n|\n|-\n|''[[Wish I Was Here]]''\n| Grace Bloom\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 2015\n| ''[[Borealis (2015 film)|Borealis]]''\n| Aurora \n|\n|-\n| ''[[Stonewall (2015 film)|Stonewall]]''\n| Phoebe Winters\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Independence Day: Resurgence]]''\n| Samantha \"Sam\" Blackwell\n| \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\" | 2017\n| ''[[Going in Style (2017 film)|Going in Style]]''\n| Brooklyn\n|\n|-\n|''[[Smartass]]''\n| Freddie\n|\n|-\n| ''[[Wish Upon]]''\n| Clare Shannon\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2018\n| data-sort-value=\"Kissing Booth 1, The\" | ''[[The Kissing Booth]]''\n|