nolin |first2=Federico L. |year=2009 |title=Primer registro f\u00f3sil de la familia Trichomycteridae (Teleostei: Siluriformes; Plioceno) en la Formaci\u00f3n Monte Hermoso, Argentina |url=http://www.scielo.org.ar/pdf/rmacn/v11n2/v11n2a05.pdf |journal=[[Revista del Museo de Ciencias Naturales]] |volume=11 |pages=193\u2013198 |accessdate=2018-09-10}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Verzi |first=Diego H. |last2=Montalvo |first2=Claudia I. |last3=Deschamps |first3=Cecilia M. |year=2008 |title=Biostratigraphy and biochronology of the Late Miocene of central Argentina: Evidence from rodents and taphonomy |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/248616305_Biostratigraphy_and_biochronology_of_the_Late_Miocene_of_central_Argentina_Evidence_from_rodents_and_taphonomy\n|journal=[[Geobios]] |volume=41 |pages=145\u2013155 |ref=harv |accessdate=2017-08-15}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Cozzuol |first=Mario Alberto |year=2006 |title=The Acre vertebrate fauna: Age, diversity, and geography |url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/222357514_The_Acre_vertebrate_fauna_Age_diversity_and_geography |journal=[[Journal of South American Earth Sciences]] |volume=21 |pages=185\u2013203 |ref=harv |accessdate=2017-08-15}}\n* {{cite LSA |last=Marshall |first=Larry G. |last2=Sempere |first2=Thierry |year=1991 |title=The Eocene to Pleistocene vertebrates of Bolivia and their stratigraphic context: A review |url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Thierry_Sempere/publication/32979728_The_Eocene_to_Pleistocene_vertebrates_of_Bolivia_and_their_stratigraphic_context_A_review/links/0f317537fb9dab3d2a000000/The-Eocene-to-Pleistocene-vertebrates-of-Bolivia-and-their-stratigraphic-context-A-review.pdf\n|journal=Revista t\u00e9cnica de YPFB |volume=12 |pages=631\u2013652 |ref=harv |accessdate=2017-08-15}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://snakesarelong.blogspot.com/2012/11/snakes-that-polish-their-scales-and-why.html Psammophids at Life is Short but Snakes are Long]\n{{Commons and category|position=left|Colubridae}}\n\n{{Snake_families}}\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q182751}}\n\n[[Category:Colubrids|.]]\n[[Category:Snake families]]\n[[Category:Cenozoic taxonomic families]]\n[[Category:Cenozoic reptiles]]\n[[Category:Extant Oligocene first appearances]]\n[[Category:Taxa described in 1881]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Nicolaus Michael Oppel]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Family of snakes}}\n{{Automatic taxobox\n| fossil_range  = [[Oligocene]] to Recent\n| image = Coluber caspius.jpg\n| image_caption = Caspian whipsnake, ''[[Coluber caspius]]''\n| taxon = Colubridae\n| authority = [[Nicolaus Michael Oppel|Oppel]], 1811\n}}\n\n'''Colubridae''' ({{IPAc-en|k|\u0259|\u02c8|l|u\u02d0|b|r|\u026a|d|i\u02d0}}, commonly known as '''colubrids''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u0252|lj|\u028a|b|r|\u026a|d|z}}, from [[Latin]] ''coluber'', snake) is a [[Family (biology)|family]] of [[snake]]s. With 249 [[Genus|genera]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Colubrid |url=https://www.britannica.com/animal/colubrid |website=britannica.com |publisher=Britannica |accessdate=2 December 2018}}</ref> it is the largest snake family. The earliest species of the family date back to the [[Oligocene]] epoch. Colubrid snakes are found on every continent except Antarctica.<ref name=EoR>{{cite book |editor=Cogger, H.G. |editor-link=Harold Cogger |editor2=Zweifel, R.G. |editor2-link=Richard G. Zweifel|author= Bauer, Aaron M.|year=1998|title=Encyclopedia of Reptiles and Amphibians|publisher= Academic Press|location=San Diego|pages= 188\u2013195|isbn= 0-12-178560-2|author-link=:fr:Aaron Matthew Bauer }}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nWhile most colubrids are not [[venom]]ous (or have venom that is not known to be harmful to humans) and are mostly harmless, a few groups, such as genus ''[[Boiga]]'', can produce medically significant bites, while the [[boomslang]], the [[twig snake]]s, and the Asian genus ''[[Rhabdophis]]'' have caused human fatalities.<ref name=EoR/><ref name=\"Bruna Azara 1995\">{{cite journal | author = Bruna Azara, C. | year = 1995 | title = Animales venenosos. Vertebrados terrestres venenosos peligrosos para el ser humano en Espa\u00f1a | url = http://www.sea-entomologia.org/PDF/BOLETIN_11/B11-009-032.pdf | journal = Bolet\u00edn de la S.E.A. | volume = 11 | issue = | pages = 32\u201340 }}</ref><ref name=\"Weinstein2011\">{{cite book|last1=Weinstein|first1=S. A.|last2=Warrell|first2=D. A.|last3=White|first3=J.|last4=Keyler|first4=D. E.|title=Venomous bites from non-venomous snakes: A critical analysis of risk and management of \"colubrid\" snake bites|date=2011|publisher=Elsevier|location=London}}</ref>\n\nSome Colubridae snakes are venomous but not all are deadly. More research needs to be done on this according to Scott Weinstein, author of \"Venomous bites from Non-Venomous snakes\". Some colubrids are described as [[snake dentition|opisthoglyphous]], meaning they have elongated, grooved teeth located in the back of their upper jaws, often called \"rear-fanged\". Opisthoglyphous dentition likely evolved many times in the history of snakes<ref name=\"Bruna Azara 1995\"/> and is an evolutionary precursor to the fangs of [[Viperidae|vipers]] and [[elapids]], which are located in the front of the mouth.<ref name=\"Jackson2003\">{{cite journal|last1=Jackson|first1=K|title=The evolution of venom-delivery systems in snakes|journal=Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society|date=2003|volume=137|issue=3|pages=337\u2013354|url=http://people.whitman.edu/~jacksok/ZJLS.pdf|doi=10.1046/j.1096-3642.2003.00052.x}}</ref><ref name=\"Vonk2008\">{{cite journal|last1=Vonk|first1=F. J.|last2=Admiraal|first2=J. F.|last3=Jackson|first3=K.|last4=Reshef|first4=R.|last5=de Bakker|first5=M. A.|last6=Vanderschoot|first6=K.|last7=van den Berge|first7=I.|last8=van Atten|first8=M.|last9=Burgerhout|first9=E.|last10=Beck|first10=A.|title=Evolutionary origin and development of snake fangs|journal=Nature|date=2008|volume=454|issue=7204|pages=630\u2013633|url=http://people.whitman.edu/~jacksok/nature.pdf|doi=10.1038/nature07178|pmid=18668106}}</ref><ref name=\"Fryetal2012\">{{cite journal|last1=Fry|first1=B. G.|last2=Casewell|first2=N. R.|last3=W\u00fcster|first3=W.|last4=Vidal|first4=N.|last5=Young|first5=B.|last6=Jackson|first6=T. N.|title=The structural and functional diversification of the Toxicofera reptile venom system|journal=Toxicon|date=2012|volume=60|issue=4|pages=434\u2013448|url=http://pages.bangor.ac.uk/~bss166/Publications/2012_Toxicofera_Toxicon.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.toxicon.2012.02.013|pmid=22446061}}</ref><ref name=EoR/><ref name=\"Bruna Azara 1995\"/>\n\n==Classification==\nIn the past, the Colubridae were not a [[monophyly|natural group]], as many were more closely related to other groups, such as [[Elapidae|elapids]], than to each other.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Lawson, R. |author2=Slowinski, J.B. |author2-link=Joseph Bruno Slowinski |author3=Crother, B.I. |author4=Burbrink, F.T. |title=Phylogeny of the Colubroidea (Serpentes): New evidence from mitochondrial and nuclear genes |url=http://naherpetology.org/pdf_files/400.pdf |year=2005 |journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution |volume=37 |issue=2 |pages=581\u2013601 |pmid=16172004 |doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2005.07.016 |access-date=2010-12-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727105819/http://naherpetology.org/pdf_files/400.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> This family was historically used as a \"[[wastebasket taxon]]\"<ref name=\"WeinsteinWarrell2011\">{{cite book|author1=Scott A Weinstein|author2=David A Warrell|author3=Julian White|author4=Daniel E Keyler|title=\"Venomous Bites from Non-Venomous Snakes: A Critical Analysis of Risk and Management of \"Colubrid Snake Bites|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lB3FxFG5wrQC&pg=PA1|date=20 June 2011|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=978-0-12-387755-0|page=1}}</ref> for snakes that do not fit elsewhere.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Fry, B.G. |author2=Vidal, N. |author3=van der Weerd, L. |author4=Kochva, E. |author5=Renjifo, C. |title=Evolution and diversification of the Toxicofera reptile venom system | year=2009 |journal=Journal of Proteomics |volume=72 |issue=2 |pages=127\u2013136 |doi=10.1016/j.jprot.2009.01.009 |pmid=19457354}}</ref> Until recently, colubrids were basically [[Colubroidea|colubroids]] that were not [[Elapidae|elapids]], [[Viperidae|viperids]], or ''[[Atractaspis]]''.<ref name=\"HerpText\">{{cite book|last1=Pough|first1=F. H.|last2=Andrews|first2=R. M.|last3=Cadle|first3=J. E.|last4=Crump|first4=M. L.|last5=Savitzky|first5=A. H.|last6=Wells|first6=K.|title=Herpetology|date=2004|publisher=Prentice Hall|location=Upper Saddle River (NJ)|isbn=0138508763|page=162|edition=3rd}}</ref>\n\nHowever, recent research in molecular phylogenetics has stabilized the classification of historically \"colubrid\" snakes and the family as currently defined is a [[monophyly|monophyletic]] [[clade]],<ref name=\"Pyronetal2013\">{{cite journal|last1=Pyron|first1=R. A.|last2=Burbrink|first2=F.|last3=Wiens|first3=J. J.|title=A phylogeny and revised classification of Squamata, including 4161 species of lizards and snakes|journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology|date=2013|volume=13|pages=93|doi=10.1186/1471-2148-13-93|pmid=23627680|pmc=3682911}}</ref><ref name=\"Figueroa16\">{{cite journal|last1=Figueroa|first1=A.|last2=McKelvy|first2=A. D.|last3=Grismer|first3=L. L.|last4=Bell|first4=C. D.|last5=Lailvaux|first5=S. P.|title=A species-level phylogeny of extant snakes with description of a new colubrid subfamily and genus|journal=PLOS ONE|date=2016|volume=11|issue=9|pages=e0161070|pmc=5014348|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0161070|pmid=27603205}}</ref><ref name=\"Pyronetal2011\">{{cite journal|last1=Pyron|first1=R. A.|last2=Burbrink|first2=F. T.|last3=Colli|first3=G. R.|last4=de Oca|first4=A. N. M.|last5=Vitt|first5=L. J.|last6=Kuczynski|first6=C. A.|last7=Wiens|first7=J. J.|title=The phylogeny of advanced snakes (Colubroidea), with discovery of a new subfamily and comparison of support methods for likelihood trees|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|date=2011|volume=58|issue=2|pages=329\u2013342|url=http://www.wienslab.com/Publications_files/Pyron_et_al_2011.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2010.11.006|pmid=21074626}}</ref><ref name=\"ZhengWiens2016\">{{cite journal|last1=Zheng|first1=Y|last2=Wiens|first2=JJ|title=Combining phylogenomic and supermatrix approaches, and a time-calibrated phylogeny for squamate reptiles (lizards and snakes) based on 52 genes and 4162 species|journal=Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution|date=2016|volume=94|issue=Pt B|pages=537\u2013547|url=http://www.wienslab.com/Publications_files/Zheng_Wiens_2015b_MPE.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.ympev.2015.10.009|pmid=26475614}}</ref> although additional research will be necessary to sort out all the relationships within this group. As of May 2018 eight subfamilies are recognized.<ref name=\"TRD\">{{cite web|last1=Uetz|first1=Peter|title=Colubridae at The Reptile Database|url=http://reptile-database.reptarium.cz/advanced_search?taxon=Colubridae&submit=Search|website=The Reptile Database|publisher=EMBL|accessdate=13 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Current subfamilies===\n\n'''[[Sibynophiinae]]''' \u2013 2 genera\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|\n* ''[[Scaphiodontophis]]''\n* ''[[Sibynophis]]''\n}}\n\n'''[[Natricinae]]''' \u2013 37 genera (sometimes given as family [[Natricidae]])\n[[Image:Indian Rat Snake (Grey and Yellow).jpg|240px|thumb|[[Ptyas mucosa|Indian Rat Snake (Grey and Yellow)]]]]\n[[Image:Coast_Garter_Snake.jpg|240px|thumb|A [[Natricinae|natricine]], ''[[Thamnophis sirtalis]]'']]\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|\n* ''[[Adelophis]]''\n* ''[[Afronatrix]]''\n* ''[[Amphiesma]]''\n* ''[[Amphiesmoides]]''\n* ''[[Anoplohydrus]]''\n* ''[[Aspidura]]''\n* ''[[Atretium]]''\n* ''[[Clonophis]]''\n* ''[[Fowlea]]''\n* ''[[Haldea striatula|Haldea]]''\n* ''[[Hebius]]''\n* ''[[Helophis]]''\n* ''[[Herpetoreas]]''\n* ''[[Hydrablabes]]''\n* ''[[Hydraethiops]]''\n* ''[[Iguanognathus]]''\n* ''[[Isanophis]]''\n* ''[[Limnophis]]''\n* ''[[Liodytes]]''\n* ''[[Natriciteres]]''\n* ''[[Natrix]]''\n* ''[[Nerodia]]''\n* ''[[Opisthotropis]]''\n* ''[[Paratapinophis]]''\n* ''[[Pseudagkistrodon]]''\n* ''[[Regina (genus)|Regina]]''\n* ''[[Rhabdophis]]''\n* ''[[Rhabdops]]''\n* ''[[Sinonatrix]]''\n* ''[[Smithophis]]''\n* ''[[Storeria]]''\n* ''[[Thamnophis]]''\n* ''[[Trachischium]]''\n* ''[[Tropidoclonion]]''\n* ''[[Tropidonophis]]''\n* ''[[Smooth earth snake|Virginia]]''\n* ''[[Xenochrophis]]''\n}}\n\n'''[[Pseudoxenodontinae]]''' \u2013 2 genera\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|\n* ''[[Plagiopholis]]''\n* ''[[Pseudoxenodon]]''\n}}\n\n'''[[Dipsadinae]]''' \u2013 98 genera (sometimes given as family [[Dipsadidae]])\n[[Image:Sibon_longifrenis_(La_Selva_Biological_Station).jpg|240px|thumb|A [[Dipsadinae|dipsadine]], ''[[Sibon longifrenis]]'']]\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|\n* ''[[Adelphicos]]''\n* ''[[Alsophis]]'' \n* ''[[Amastridium]]''\n* ''[[Amnesteophis]]''\n* ''[[Apostolepis]]''\n* ''[[Arcanumophis]]''\n* ''[[Arrhyton]]''\n* ''[[Atractus]]''\n* ''[[Boiruna]]''\n* ''[[Borikenophis]]''\n* ''[[Caaeteboia]]''\n* ''[[Calamodontophis]]''\n* ''[[Caraiba]]''\n* ''[[Carphophis]]''\n* ''[[Cenaspis]]''\n* ''[[Cercophis]]''\n* ''[[Chersodromus]]''\n* ''[[Clelia (snake)|Clelia]]''\n* ''[[Coniophanes]]''\n* ''[[Conophis]]''\n* ''[[Contia]]''\n* ''[[Coronelaps]]''\n* ''[[Crisantophis]]''\n* ''[[Cryophis]]''\n* ''[[Cubophis]]''\n* ''[[Diadophis]]''\n* ''[[Diaphorolepis]]''\n* ''[[Dipsas]]''\n* ''[[Ditaxodon]]''\n* ''[[Drepanoides]]''\n* ''[[Echinanthera]]''\n* ''[[Elapomorphus]]''\n* ''[[Emmochliophis]]''\n* ''[[Enuliophis]]''\n* ''[[Enulius]]''\n* ''[[Erythrolamprus]]''\n* ''[[Eutrachelophis]]''\n* ''[[Farancia]]''\n* ''[[Geophis]]''\n* ''[[Gomesophis]]''\n* ''[[Haitiophis]]''\n* ''[[Helicops (genus)|Helicops]]''\n* ''[[Heterodon]]''\n* ''[[Hydrodynastes]]''\n* ''[[Hydromorphus]]''\n* ''[[Hydrops (genus)|Hydrops]]''\n* ''[[Hypsiglena]]''\n* ''[[Hypsirhynchus]]''\n* ''[[Ialtris]]''\n* ''[[Imantodes]]''\n* ''[[Leptodeira]]''\n* ''[[Lioheterophis]]''\n* ''[[Lygophis]]''\n* ''[[Magliophis]]''\n* ''[[Manolepis]]''\n* ''[[Mussurana (genus)|Mussurana]]''\n* ''[[Ninia]]''\n* ''[[Nothopsis]]''\n* ''[[Omoadiphas]]''\n* ''[[Oxyrhopus]]''\n* ''[[Paraphimophis]]''\n* ''[[Phalotris]]''\n* ''[[Philodryas]]''\n* ''[[Phimophis]]''\n* ''[[Plesiodipsas]]''\n* ''[[Pliocercus]]''\n* ''[[Pseudalsophis]]''\n* ''[[Pseudoboa]]''\n* ''[[Pseudoeryx]]''\n* ''[[Pseudoleptodeira]]''\n* ''[[Pseudotomodon]]''\n* ''[[Psomophis]]''\n* ''[[Ptychophis]]''\n* ''[[Rhachidelus]]''\n* ''[[Rhadinaea]]''\n* ''[[Rhadinella]]''\n* ''[[Rhadinophanes]]''\n* ''[[Rodriguesophis]]''\n* ''[[Saphenophis]]''\n* ''[[Sibon (genus)|Sibon]]''\n* ''[[Siphlophis]]''\n* ''[[Sordellina]]''\n* ''[[Synophis]]''\n* ''[[Tachymenis]]''\n* ''[[Taeniophallus]]''\n* ''[[Tantalophis]]''\n* ''[[Thamnodynastes]]''\n* ''[[Thermophis]]''\n* ''[[Tomodon]]''\n* ''[[Tretanorhinus]]''\n* ''[[Trimetopon]]''\n* ''[[Tropidodipsas]]''\n* ''[[Tropidodryas]]''\n* ''[[Uromacer]]''\n* ''[[Urotheca]]''\n* ''[[Xenodon]]''\n* ''[[Xenopholis]]''\n}}\n\n'''[[Grayiinae]]''' \u2013 1 genus\n* ''[[Grayia (snake)|Grayia]]''\n\n'''[[Calamariinae]]''' \u2013 7 genera\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|\n* ''[[Calamaria]]''\n* ''[[Calamorhabdium]]''\n* ''[[Collorhabdium]]''\n* ''[[Etheridgeum]]''\n* ''[[Macrocalamus]]''\n* ''[[Pseudorabdion]]''\n* ''[[Rabdion]]''\n}}\n\n'''[[Ahaetuliinae]]''' \u2013 5 genera\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|\n* ''[[Ahaetulla]]''\n* ''[[Chrysopelea]]''\n* ''[[Dendrelaphis]]''\n* ''[[Dryophiops]]''\n* ''[[Proahaetulla]]''}}\n\n'''[[Colubrinae]]''' \u2013 92 genera\n[[Image:PikiWiki Israel 37648 Nature and Colors.jpg|240px|thumb|A [[Colubrinae|colubrine]], ''[[Dolichophis jugularis]]'', preying on a legless lizard, a [[sheltopusik]]]]\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|\n* ''[[Aeluroglena]]''\n* ''[[Aprosdoketophis]]''\n* ''[[Archelaphe]]''\n* ''[[Argyrogena]]''\n* ''[[Arizona (snake)|Arizona]]''\n* ''[[Bamanophis]]''\n* ''[[Bogertophis]]''\n* ''[[Boiga]]''\n* ''[[Cemophora]]''\n* ''[[Chapinophis]]''\n* ''[[Chironius]]''\n* ''[[Coelognathus]]''\n* ''[[Eastern racer|Coluber]]''\n* ''[[Colubroelaps]]''\n* ''[[Conopsis]]''\n* ''[[Coronella]]''\n* ''[[Crotaphopeltis]]''\n* ''[[Dasypeltis]]''\n* ''[[Dendrophidion]]''\n* ''[[Dipsadoboa]]''\n* ''[[Dispholidus]]''\n* ''[[Dolichophis]]''\n* ''[[Drymarchon]]''\n* ''[[Drymobius]]''\n* ''[[Drymoluber]]''\n* ''[[Eirenis]]''\n* ''[[Elaphe]]''\n* ''[[Euprepiophis]]''\n* ''[[Ficimia]]''\n* ''[[Geagras]]''\n* ''[[Gonyosoma]]''\n* ''[[Gyalopion]]''\n* ''[[Hapsidophrys]]''\n* ''[[Hemerophis]]''\n* ''[[Hemorrhois]]''\n* ''[[Hierophis]]''\n* ''[[Kingsnake|Lampropeltis]]''\n* ''[[Leptodrymus]]''\n* ''[[Leptophis]]''\n* ''[[Liopeltis]]''\n* ''[[Lycodon]]''\n* ''[[Lytorhynchus]]''\n* ''[[Macroprotodon]]''\n* ''[[Masticophis]]''\n* ''[[Mastigodryas]]''\n* ''[[Meizodon]]''\n* ''[[Mopanveldophis]]''\n* ''[[Muhtarophis]]''\n* ''[[Oligodon]]''\n* ''[[Oocatochus]]''\n* ''[[Opheodrys]]''\n* ''[[Oreocryptophis]]''\n* ''[[Orientocoluber]]''\n* ''[[Oxybelis]]''\n* ''[[Palusophis]]''\n* ''[[Pantherophis]]''\n* ''[[Philothamnus]]''\n* ''[[Phrynonax]]''\n* ''[[Phyllorhynchus]]''\n* ''[[Pituophis]]''\n* ''[[Platyceps]]''\n* ''[[Pseudelaphe]]''\n* ''[[Pseudoficimia]]''\n* ''[[Ptyas]]''\n* ''[[Rhamnophis]]''\n* ''[[Rhinobothryum]]''\n* ''[[Rhinocheilus]]''\n* ''[[Rhynchocalamus]]''\n* ''[[Salvadora (snake)|Salvadora]]''\n* ''[[Scaphiophis]]''\n* ''[[Scolecophis]]''\n* ''[[Senticolis]]''\n* ''[[Simophis]]''\n* ''[[Sonora (genus)|Sonora]]''\n* ''[[Spalerosophis]]''\n* ''[[Spilotes]]''\n* ''[[Stegonotus (snake)|Stegonotus]]''\n* ''[[Stenorrhina]]''\n* ''[[Stichophanes]]''\n* ''[[Symphimus]]''\n* ''[[Sympholis]]''\n* ''[[Tantilla]]''\n* ''[[Tantillita]]''\n* ''[[Telescopus]]''\n* ''[[Thelotornis]]''\n* ''[[Thrasops]]''\n* ''[[Toxicodryas]]''\n* ''[[Trimorphodon]]''\n* ''[[Wallaceophis]]''\n* ''[[Xenelaphis]]''\n* ''[[Xyelodontophis]]''\n* ''[[Zamenis]]''\n}}\n\n'''genera ''[[incertae sedis]]''''' (not currently placed in a subfamily, usually because of the absence of genetic data, but suspected to be colubrids based on morphology)\n{{columns-list|colwidth=15em|\n*''[[Blythia]]''\n*''[[Elapoidis]]''\n*''[[Gongylosoma]]''\n*''[[Lycognathophis]]''\n*''[[Oreocalamus (snake)|Oreocalamus]]''\n*{{extinct}}''[[Paraxenophis]]''\n*{{extinct}}''[[Periergophis]]''\n*''[[Poecilopholis]]''\n*''[[Tetralepis]]''\n}}\n\n===Former subfamilies===\nThese taxa have been at one time or another classified as part of the Colubridae, but are now either classified as parts of other families, or are no longer accepted because all the species within them have been moved to other (sub)families.\n\n* Subfamily [[Aparallactinae]] (now a subfamily of [[Lamprophiidae]],<ref name=\"Pyronetal2011\"/> sometimes combined with [[Atractaspidinae]])\n* Subfamily Boiginae (now part of [[Colubrinae]])\n* Subfamily Boodontinae (some of which now treated as subfamily [[Grayiinae]] of the new Colubridae, others moved to family [[Lamprophiidae]] as subfamilies [[Lamprophiinae]] and [[Pseudaspidinae]])\n* Subfamily Dispholidinae (now part of Colubrinae)\n* Subfamily [[Homalopsinae]] (now family [[Homalopsidae]]<ref name=\"Pyronetal2011\"/>)\n* Subfamily Lamprophiinae (now a subfamily of Lamprophiidae<ref name=\"Pyronetal2011\"/>)\n* Subfamily Lycodontinae (now part of Colubrinae)\n* Subfamily Lycophidinae (now part of Lamprophiidae)\n* Subfamily Pareatinae (now family [[Pareidae]],<ref name=\"Pyronetal2011\"/> sometimes incorrectly spelled Pareatidae<ref name=Savage>{{cite journal |last1=Savage |first1=Jay M. |year=2015 |title=What are the correct family names for the taxa that include the snake genera ''Xenodermus'', ''Pareas'', and ''Calamaria''? |journal=Herpetological Review |volume=46 |issue=4 |pages=664\u2013665 |url=http://www.zenscientist.com/index.php/pdflibrary2/func-finishdown/2496/ |access-date=2018-05-14 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307141006/http://www.zenscientist.com/index.php/pdflibrary2/func-finishdown/2496/ |archive-date=2016-03-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>)\n* Subfamily Philothamninae (now part of Colubrinae)\n* Subfamily [[Psammophiinae]] (now a subfamily of Lamprophiidae<ref name=\"Pyronetal2011\"/>)\n* Subfamily [[Pseudoxyrhophiinae]] (now a subfamily of Lamprophiidae<ref name=\"Pyronetal2011\"/>)\n* Subfamily Xenoderminae (now family [[Xenodermidae]],<ref name=\"Pyronetal2011\"/> sometimes incorrectly spelled Xenodermatidae<ref name=Savage/>)\n* Subfamily [[Xenodontinae]] (which many authors put in [[Dipsadinae]]/[[Dipsadidae]])\n\n== Fossil Colubridae ==\n\n=== North America ===\n;Mexico\n{{Location map+ | Mexico\n| relief = 1\n| width   = 400\n| caption = Locations of Colubridae fossil finds in Mexico<br>[[File:White pog.svg|14px]] [[Cueva de Abra Travertine]]<br>[[File:Yellow ffff80 pog.svg|14px]]  [[Goleta Formation#]]<br>[[File:Yellow pog.svg|14px]] Las Tunas Wash; Jeffries Site\n| places  =\n  {{Location map~ | Mexico\n  | lat_deg = 19.7\n  | lon_deg = -101.1\n  | mark = Yellow ffff80 pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = Goleta Formation#Fossil content\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | Mexico\n  | lat_deg = 22.4\n  | lon_deg = -98.0\n  | mark = White pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = Cueva de Abra Travertine\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | Mexico\n  | lat_deg = 23.3\n  | lon_deg = -109.6\n  | mark = Yellow pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = \n  }}\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\"\n! Find !! [[North American land mammal age|NALMA]] !! Formation !! Notes !! Refs\n|-\n| [[Colubrinae|Colubrinae indet.]] || style=\"background-color: {{period color|pleistocene}};\" | [[Pleistocene]] || [[Cueva de Abra Travertine]] || Described from Cueva de Abra Travertine in [[Tamaulipas State|Tamaulipas]] by {{small|{{smallcaps|W. W. Dalquest and E. Roth. 1970. Late Pleistocene mammals from a cave in Tamaulipas, Mexico. Southwestern Naturalist 15(2):217-230}}}} || align=center | <ref>[http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?a=collectionSearch&collection_no=71264 Fossilworks]</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Pituophis|?Pituophis sp.]]'' || style=\"background-color: {{period color|pliocene}};\" | [[Blancan]] ||  || Described from Las Tunas Wash; Jeffries Site in [[Baja California Sur State|Baja California Sur]] by {{small|{{smallcaps|W. E. Miller. 1980. The Late Pliocene Las Tunas Local Fauna from Southernmost Baja California, Mexico. Journal of Paleontology 54(4):762-805}}}} || align=center | <ref>[http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?a=collectionSearch&collection_no=19673 Fossilworks]</ref>\n|-\n| ''[[Lampropeltis intermedius]]'' || style=\"background-color: {{period color|pliocene}};\" | [[Blancan]] || [[Goleta Formation|Goleta]] || Described from locality in [[Michoac\u00e1n State|Michoac\u00e1n]] by {{small|{{smallcaps|C. A. Repenning. 1962. The Giant Ground Squirrel Paenemarmota. Journal of Paleontology 36(3):540-556}}}} || align=center | <ref>[http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?a=collectionSearch&collection_no=20072 Fossilworks]</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n=== South America ===\n{{Location map+ | South America\n| relief = 1\n| width   = 400\n| caption = Locations of Colubridae fossil finds in South America<br>[[File:White pog.svg|14px]] Pleisto-Holocene ages<br>[[File:Yellow ffff80 pog.svg|14px]]  Pliocene ages<br>[[File:Yellow pog.svg|14px]] Miocene ages\n| places  =\n  {{Location map~ | South America\n  | lat_deg = -38.971835\n  | lon_deg = -61.323988\n  | mark = Yellow ffff80 pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = Brochero Formation#Fossil content\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | South America\n  | lat_deg = -38.242134\n  | lon_deg = -61.880212\n  | mark = Yellow ffff80 pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = Monte Hermoso Formation#Fossil content\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | South America\n  | lat_deg = -37.4\n  | lon_deg = -65.5\n  | mark = Yellow pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = Cerro Azul Formation#Fossil content\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | South America\n  | lat_deg = -8.8\n  | lon_deg = -68.8\n  | mark = Yellow pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = Solim\u00f5es Formation#Fossil content\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | South America\n  | lat_deg = 5.191944\n  | lon_deg = -74.7225\n  | mark = Yellow pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = Honda Group, Colombia#Fossil content\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | South America\n  | lat_deg = -20.8\n  | lon_deg = -63.1\n  | mark = White pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = \u00d1uapua Formation#Fossil content\n  }}\n  {{Location map~ | South America\n  | lat_deg = -50.0\n  | lon_deg = -70.0\n  | mark = Yellow pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = Santa Cruz Formation#Fossil content\n  }}\n   {{Location map~ | South America\n  | lat_deg = -45.737665\n  | lon_deg = -68.771670\n  | mark = Yellow pog.svg\n  | marksize = 12\n  | link = Sarmiento Formation#Fossil content\n  }}\n}}\n;Legend\n* Age - '''bold''' is [[type locality (geology)|type age]] ([[South American land mammal age|SALMA]])\n* Formation - '''bold''' is [[:Category:Lagerst\u00e4tten|Lagerst\u00e4tte]]\n\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable mw-collapsible\"\n! Find !! [[South American land mammal age|SALMA]] !! Basin !! Formation !! Country !! Notes !! Refs\n|-\n| {{small|\"Colubridae sp.\" ''[[sic]]''}} || style=\"background-color: {{period color|serravallian}};\" | '''[[Laventan]]''' || [[Upper Magdalena Valley|VSM]] || '''[[Honda Group, Colombia#Villavieja Formation|Villavieja]]''' || {{COL}} || Described from same Los Mangos Fishbed in [[Huila Department|Huila]]; ''[[Colombophis|Colombophis portai]]'' and ''[[Eunectes stirtoni]]'' by {{small|{{smallcaps|R. Hoffstetter and J.-C. Rage. 1977. Le gisement de vert\u00e9br\u00e9s Mioc\u00e8nes de La Venta (Colombie) et sa faune de serpents. Annales de Pal\u00e9ontologie (Vert\u00e9br\u00e9s) 63(2):161-190}}}} || align=center | <ref>[http://fossilworks.org/bridge.pl?a=collectionSearch&collection_no=186058 Fossilworks]</ref>\n|-\n| indet. || style=\"background-color: {{period color|tortonian}};\" | [[Chasicoan]]<br>[[Mayoan]]<br>[[Laventan]] || [[Solim\u00f5es Basin|Solim\u00f5es]]